<h2>Causes of the French Revolution</h2>
<p>As the 18th century drew to a close, France’s costly involvement in the American Revolution, combined with extravagant spending by King Louis XVI and his court, had left France on the brink of bankruptcy.</p>
<p>Not only were the royal coffers depleted, but several years of poor harvests, drought, cattle disease and skyrocketing bread prices from bad harvests had kindled unrest among peasants and the urban poor. Many expressed their desperation and resentment toward a regime that imposed heavy taxes—yet failed to provide any relief—by rioting, looting and striking.</p>
<p>In the fall of 1786, Louis XVI’s controller general, Charles Alexandre de Calonne, proposed a financial reform package that included a universal land tax from which the aristocratic classes would no longer be exempt.</p>

